# bsh playground

Press <CR> (Enter) on a cell to run it. Re-run any cell to refresh its result
in place -- the ```out / ```dir blocks below a cell are owned by bsh. `za` folds
a result block. This file is a `.bsh`, so cells are live the moment you open it.


## one-shot shell   (<CR> = inline output; <C-CR> or g<CR> = output to a side buffer)

% echo "hello from a fresh shell"; uname -s

## try g<CR> on the next line: output goes to a bsh://out buffer, <CR> the ref to open it

% for i in $(seq 5); do echo "line $i"; done


## persistent session -- env / cwd carry across cells

%% export GREETING=hi; cd /tmp
%% echo "$GREETING from $(pwd)"


## multiline (run <CR> anywhere inside the fence)

```%%
for i in 1 2 3; do
  echo "line $i"
done
```


## python -- one-shot (%) vs session (%%)

```python %
print("one-shot:", 2 ** 10)
```

```python %%
import math
r = 3
```

```python %%
print("area =", round(math.pi * r * r, 2))   # sees r + math from the cell above
```


## listing & navigation  (<CR> on an entry drills in / opens)

: ~

: goto pockt


## namespace -- your $BSH_HOME command tree
## (point BSH_HOME at examples/bsh-home to try these)

llm.tools.weather

llm.tools.weather Ankara

llm.tools.weather Ankara | tr a-z A-Z

llm.tools.reverse hello

## define/edit a command in place: foo.bar! opens its source
## (scaffolds a new executable, after a confirm, if it doesn't exist yet)

demo.weather!

demo.

demo.menu

demo.greet


## agent (needs the `llm` CLI) -- >> folds in the cell above as context

> say hello in one short sentence
